Hi Zaris,
Thank you for taking the time to speak with me today! I have added the
details of the full interview round below for your review. Please let me
know if you have any questions on the materials.

You will soon receive another email to submit your availability for the
interviews.

Systems Programming

In this interview, you will be given a specific question focused on systems
programming. The question is usually on a single computer/single machine
(e.g. design and implement a single-machine cache) and you=E2=80=99ll be as=
ked to
produce a relevant and performant system. The question is likely to be a
general question, and not necessarily related to your technical background
or to Databricks=E2=80=99 core products. We are evaluating your technical
knowledge/solution as well as your communication around that solution.


You will need to ask clarifying questions and fully understand the paramete=
rs
of the problem before solving. Requirements to consider while solving are
including but not limited to performance, concurrency, threading versus
multi-threading, and order dependent processing. Additional sample design
requirements are better throughput, reducing latency, and data durability.Y=
ou
will also want to consider things like synchronization, network and disk IO=
.

The desired outcome of this interview is an actual pseudocode
implementation that is reliable, fast, scalable, and covers any other
predetermined requirements. You will be asked to implement various parts of
the system and write pseudocode that effectively conveys your solution. You
will not be expected to write compiling code, and it doesn=E2=80=99t need t=
o be in
a specific language, but you should be ready to write sufficiently specific
code to have a conversation around tradeoffs, techniques, and solutions
related to the above. You should be familiar with structuring of classes,
strong cohesion and weak coupling, separation of concerns, and single
responsibility
principle.


It is also essential to think about ways things may fail under concurrency
and environmental conditions, and to provide reasoning on how to handle
them=E2=80=93 The interviewer may add in additional parameters or requireme=
nts as
the interview progresses (e.g. =E2=80=9Chow would you handle losing power o=
n a
regular basis=E2=80=9D). These questions typically relate back to real worl=
d
circumstances.


The expectation is that you are driving the solution and proactively
explaining/rationalizing your solution and decisions. The interviewer
should be open to discuss parameters and requirements wit you upfront, and
answer any questions you may have while solving. There may be circumstances
in which the interviewer feels the solution is not going in a direction
they had hoped; they might give you a hint or try to steer you in a new
direction. It is equally important to listen to their feedback and apply it
to your solution. Typically, the more you talk through your process,
describe your thinking and decisions, the better the interviewer can
evaluate.


A sample design question is something like a rate limiter
<https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/how-to-design-a-rate-limiter-api-learn-syste=
m-design/>
. I have heard that concurrency and multi-threading questions on Leetcode
can be helpful.


Tooling: CoderPad



Algorithms (same format as the technical screen)

In this interview, you will be asked a question focused on typical computer
science data structures and algorithms, as well as some math concepts. The
expectation is that you will be able to code a solution that can compile
and run. You=E2=80=99ll be evaluated on your actual implementation, analysi=
s around
the implementation, as well as your communication around the solution. We
also like to see you produce appropriate test cases and that your solution
applies to corner/edge cases in a clean and concise way.

Before solving, it is recommended to briefly discuss the problem and define
your approach. While solving, please explain your decisions and thought
process=E2=80=93 we want to see that you can justify your solution. We typi=
cally
only ask one question in this interview, but the interviewer may ask follow
up questions or for clarifications around things like time complexity and
run-time performance. They may also give hints so it is important to listen
to any feedback. It is highly recommended to factor in and discuss edge
cases and tradeoffs. We expect you to test and debug your solution. We care
about clarity (what does each statement do), ordering, data flow (what
values are passed from where into where), and correct use of concurrency
primitives.

This interview is language agnostic and you can use whatever language you
feel most comfortable in or feel best suits the problem at hand.


For preparation, you can look at topics like hash maps, strings, binary
search, graphs, arrays, sorting, etc.

Tooling: CoderPad

Coding

In this interview we will evaluate your coding, implementation, and
debugging skills, replicating a typical everyday working environment.  We
want to see you write clean, bug-free, well-tested code. It is recommended
to briefly discuss the problem and define your approach. While solving, it
is also recommended to explain the decisions you=E2=80=99re making and the
correctness of the solution.


This interview is focused more on implementation than the Algorithms
interview, but you will still need some basic algorithms knowledge to solve
the problem. The first priority for this interview is a complete solution,
followed by debugging and testing edge cases for the solution. We will look
at how you implement your components, classes, methods, and functions, your
coding style, and your test cases.


Tooling: CoderPad



Conversational/Behavioral aka Cross-Functional (1 hour)

This is a conversational interview with an engineering manager here at
Databricks focused on how you operate in a working environment, your
interest in Databricks, your career growth/progression, and your technical
background.

We want to see that you can communicate clearly and concisely, that there's
a method to your answers and you provide sufficient details. When speaking
about technical details, please be conscious of your audience and ensure
you clarify any jargon/internal terminology.

Read about *the STAR method *and use it during your answers!

Generally, the topics tend to cover the below areas:



   -

   Collaboration: These questions will focus on things like conflict
   resolution, mentorship of junior engineers, managing up, and working
   cross-functionally.
   -

      I.e. Tell me about a time you had a disagreement with a teammate and
      how you solved it
      -

      I.e. Tell me about  time to have to execute on a project with varying
      stakeholder priorities
      -

   Ownership & Impact: We want to see that you can identify and solve
   problems. Similarly, we want to understand your decision making process.
   These questions may also focus on your motivation around your work and h=
ow
   you see projects end to end.
   -

      I.e. Describe a project end to end, who was involved, how did you
      measure success
      -

      I.e. A project you are leading is getting off track/set to miss a
      deadline, how do you course correct
      -

   Growth/Reflection: These questions will see if you understand how you
   can improve/have improved from the past, how you give/receive both posit=
ive
   and negative feedback, if you seek out mentors and learning opportunitie=
s,
   and your learning preferences (i.e. learning many skills or being a deep
   technical master).
   -

      Tell me about a time something went wrong/didn=E2=80=99t go as planne=
d. What
      did you learn/what would you do differently
      -

      Provide an example of a time you took some feedback and applied it to
      your day to day
      -

   Technical Background: Please be prepared to explain your background from
   a technical perspective and how it may fit with Databricks. You will lik=
ely
   be asked to multiple recent or impactful projects. (Remember, this
   interview is focused on softer skills)
   -

   Career: We'll also want to understand your overall career
   growth/history, such as why you left a company for a new opportunity.
   -

   Interest in Databricks: Please be prepared to answer why you're
   interested in Databricks.

You can also review our culture principles
<https://www.databricks.com/company/careers/culture>! While the questions
don't always directly relate, it can be good to work these themes into your
answers.


General Tips



   1.

   ASK ASK ASK clarifying questions before diving into the problem
   2.

   Walk the engineer through your thought process (thinking out loud)
   3.

   Be mindful of bugs and test-driven development
   4.

   Think about the implementability, maintainability and operability of
   your design
   5.

   Also think about trade-offs to your design and be prepared to explain
   why you picked the technologies
   6.

   If you are given hints, make sure to pay attention to them and implement
   them where you can
   7.

   Be prepared to discuss what motivations you have in your career, your
   passions, and relevant research as this all resonates with our teams.
   8.

   Subscribe and watch our Databricks Youtube Channel
   <https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC3q8O3Bh2Le8Rj1-Q-_UUbA> to glean more
   about our organization and team.
   9.

   Research the Panel Members: you will be meeting with, try to look into
   their Github repository as it will give you more information about that
   engineer, and the more you know about an individual, the better
   interactions will be experienced.
   10.

   Try our Product: Take advantage of being able to use our product for
   FREE: https://databricks.com/try-databricks
   11.

   Analyze Code Base: Spend time to look into the code of our projects:
   DeltaLake, Koala, & DataFlow Reflect and try to draw similar patterns as
   this reveals the coding culture of Databricks. Share these findings with
   your interviewers.
   12.

   Check out CTCI as it is a classic CS recommended book for interviewing.
   No one is going to ask you a question you will see in that book, but if =
you
   are comfortable solving these questions and writing the code on the
   whiteboard (or notebook) you are good to go. Time yourself and resist th=
e
   urge to type the code=E2=80=94 challenge yourself to use a whiteboard. I=
t is a
   totally different experience which feels weird at first, but it makes yo=
u a
   stronger programmer.
   13.

   "Programming Pearls" written by Jon Bentley. An awesome read that is
   written much along the lines of Strunk and White's Elements of Style abo=
ut
   writing, if you have read it. It is from the perspective of breaking dow=
n
   the coding process into smaller consumable parts and slowing down the
   teaching process many notches down. Awesome read if you have been a
   programmer all your life and want to whack in the gut with simple stuff
   that you should have known the first time you used a compiler.
   14.

   Communication and Collaboration: Here at Databricks the work is largely
   collaborative, our environment is open and transparent; as such, it=E2=
=80=99s
   important that we understand how effectively you communicate and how you
   partner with those around you. Throughout the day, we expect that you wi=
ll
   be able to verbalize your thought process clearly and actively communica=
te
   your approach.
   15.

   Clarify and Gather Requirements: Some of the problems you will face are
   deliberately open-ended. You will be required to identify the relevant
   requirements and define what problem solving technique is necessary. Avo=
id
   making assumptions and further exhibit your communication skills by taki=
ng
   a step back to assess the problem and its parameters before diving in to
   solve it.
   16.

   Seek to Improve and Iterate: Like most problems within software
   engineering the technical questions are iterative, try your best to be
   mindful of and strive to improve your solutions. We want to see that you
   can continue to refine your solution and assess tradeoffs to get to a
   reasonable end state.



Hopefully you found this information helpful in better preparing you for
what=E2=80=99s ahead. Engineering Interviews are complex and challenging so=
 ideally
this has served useful in your preparation! Don=E2=80=99t forget that this =
will
also be a great opportunity for you to learn more about us and how you
could make an impact on Databricks Engineering. Come with questions and
feel free to pick our brains! Ultimately we hope you end the day feeling
challenged and even more excited about the potential of becoming a
Brickster.

